Garissa youth have banded together to fight insecurity, drug and substance abuse and help mend inter-clan divisions. It plans to engage teenagers in businesses. The young people said youth unemployment has forced many into crime. The group also has an education department that will help improve education. Chairman Farhan Ali said the youths from different clans will work together despite their differences. Their cooperation will help them appreciate other ethni groups, Ali said. The youths said they will also engage their peers against joining extremist groups and educate them against FGM and other violence against women.